body:
In following code, the inferred type of `makeConcrete()` is `Hello|null`, but should be `Hello`:

```php
<?php

class Hello
{
    public function sayHello() : string
    {
        return 'hello';
    }
}

/**
 * @psalm-template GenericType
 * @psalm-param class-string<GenericType> $type
 * @psalm-param callable(GenericType|null $unused):void $someCallback
 * @return GenericType
 */
function makeConcrete($type, callable $someCallback)
{
    $instance = new $type;
    $someCallback($instance);
    return $instance;
}

makeConcrete(
    Hello::class,
    static function (?Hello $hi) : void
    {
        if ($hi !== null) {
            $hi->sayHello();
        }
    }
)->sayHello();
```

https://psalm.dev/r/9f8dbc691c : 

```
Psalm output (using commit 9fb9679):

ERROR: PossiblyNullReference - 32:4 - Cannot call method sayHello on possibly null value
```

If I understand it correctly, this is kinda part of the design: the closure that I gave to `makeConcrete()` has a wider type, and therefore affects the definition of `GenericType`. The problem is that this "type fitting" does not consider that I declared `GenericType|null`.

My intuition (which may be totally wrong), is that `GenericType|null` is pattern-matched as `(Hello|null)|null`, and `GenericType` is therefore being fit to `Hello|null` rather than just `Hello`.
